This photo is from series 9856 at State Records NSW, which means it came from the old Maritime Services Board to SRNSW.

That clue suggests a maritime cargo shed.

comment._content: Maritime seems more likely - it is strange because the wooden doors, walls and large windows do not look strong enough to hold the iron girder roof.  And it is very long, like a finger wharf.

comment.author: 27331537@N06
comment._content: This is a brief description of the series this image is from: These glass negatives record the construction of wharves and adjoining facilities in Sydney Harbour; ferry wharves and passenger amenities; views of Port Jackson; different types of ships and vessels; diagrams of technical systems; shipping movements; navigational aids such as buoys and beacons; rail work, tenements; roadways, housing and buildings in the harbour area including warehouses and boatsheds; road construction; reclamation works; equipment; damaged vessels (including on slipways); harbour-side pools; and demolition sites (including wharves to combat rats and the plague). See: search.records.nsw.gov.au/series/9856
